rComments: Very nice professor, tries to address every question in class and after class carefully. Lectures are interesting and informative, and he reviews material from last class at the beginning of every class. Labs and tests can be tricky, would recommend going to the assigned lab hours to consult the lab TAs.

For one of our midterms, 50% of the material was based on an obscure attack (padding oracle) he barely went over in class and wasn't found in any assignments/labs. You either got lucky and studied for it, or you didn't and you lost 50% of the marks on the midterm. Be cautious when taking this course with professor Lie...
Very interesting class to take, but exams are quite tough to do well on. All the material is grounded in real-life, so the labs and topics are interesting. The professor knows his stuff.

Loved Operating Systems. Labs are tough, time-consuming, and many people don't finish the last two, but we're expected to dive into the deep end by 3rd year. The concepts however are very easy to understand thanks to Lie's great lecturing, which also makes the exams quite straightforward. Don't worry about the labs - just do well on the exams.

Very bad professor - there is too much of a barrier between what he teaches and his labs/assignments.  Also there was nothing to study from for the midterm (no previous exams, practice problems, etc).  Although the course itself is interesting, he destroys your interest.  As long as he's teaching I'd recommend that nobody take this course.
Smartest prof at U of T! He's EngSci grad
